ce":"Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Fosseux, Nord, France":"Nord, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Adele","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adele D’Ollehain was born about 1219, her father, Pierre Ier D'OLHAIN, was 32 and her mother, Giselberthe DE NÉDON, was 22. She had at least 2 sons with Robert De Fosseux III. She died about 1269, at the age of 52."},"et":{"ABT 1219–ABT 1269":"umbes 1219–umbes 1269","1219–1269":"1219–1269","1209–1263":"1209–1263","1241–1297":"1241–1297","1241–1315":"1241–1315","1188–1240":"1188–1240","1198–1253":"1198–1253","environ 1240":"umbes 1240","1253":"1253","1198":"1198","1297":"1297","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","ABT 1269":"umbes 1269","ABT 1215":"umbes 1215","1240":"1240","ABT 1219":"umbes 1219","1315":"1315","ABT 1241":"umbes 1241","1269":"1269","1188":"1188","1209":"1209","1219":"1219","Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Fosseux, Nord, France":"Nord, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1219–ABT 1269":"noin 1219–noin 1269","1219–1269":"1219–1269","1209–1263":"1209–1263","1241–1297":"1241–1297","1241–1315":"1241–1315","1188–1240":"1188–1240","1198–1253":"1198–1253","environ 1240":"noin 1240","1253":"1253","1198":"1198","1297":"1297","1241":"1241","1263":"1263","ABT 1269":"noin 1269","ABT 1215":"noin 1215","1240":"1240","ABT 1219":"noin 1219","1315":"1315","ABT 1241":"noin 1241","1269":"1269","1188":"1188","1209":"1209","1219":"1219","Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Fresnicourt-le-Dolmen, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Ranska","Fosseux, Nord, France":"